Subcode.Label: Bridge_Span
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A section of the bridge deck between successive supports such as pillars, piers, or abutments.

Subcode.Label: Bridge_Superstruct
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Those elements of the bridge structure which are above the lowest deck. (See also AQ055)

Subcode.Label: Bridge_Pylon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A tower or pylon from which a bridge's deck is suspended.

Subcode.Label: Bridge_Pier
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The support(s) in the form of pillar(s) or abutment(s) for the spans of a bridge.

Subcode.Label: Constriction_or_Expansion
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A point where a passage way narrows or expands beyond its normal width.

Subcode.Label: Control_Tower
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A tower-like structure that houses the persons and equipment used to control the flow of air, rail, or marine traffic. (See also AL240)

Subcode.Label: Crossing
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A point where two or more line features intersect or cross at the same level about which information is required. (See also BH070)

Subcode.Label: Causeway_Structure
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A solid raised way across a terrain obstacle (for example: a wetland or a body of shallow water) that is intended to support a transportation route (for example: a road or a railway).
Subcode.Recommended_Dataset_Component: Road Network Lineal, Railroad Network Lineal

Subcode.Label: Causeway
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A raised roadway of solid structure built primarily to provide a route across wet ground or intertidal area.
Subcode.Recommended_Dataset_Component: Road Network Lineal, Railroad Network Lineal

Subcode.Label: Culvert
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A sewer or drain crossing under a road, track, or embankment, without affecting the construction of the crossed feature.

Subcode.Label: Drop_Gate
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A massive assemblage of material, usually in the form of concrete logs or blocks, positioned alongside or above a transportation route, ready to be activated as a potential barrier to an advancing enemy ground force, when needed.

Subcode.Label: Ferry_Crossing
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A route in a body of water where a ferry crosses from one shoreline to another.

Subcode.Label: Ice_Route
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A route over a frozen watercourse.

Subcode.Label: Ferry_Site
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A point where a ferry takes on or discharges its load.

Subcode.Label: Entrance_or_Exit
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A point of entrance or exit. (See also AA010 and AQ130)

Subcode.Label: Tunnel_Mouth
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The opening of a tunnel into a larger space (for example: onto the terrain surface).
Subcode.Recommended_Dataset_Component: Road Network Lineal Figure Pt, Railroad Network Lineal Figure Pt

Subcode.Label: Landmark_Post
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A marker which designates the distance from a given point, or a location.

Subcode.Label: Buried_Utility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Utilities or pipeline network that is located underground or below a waterbody.

Subcode.Label: Mooring_Mast
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A tower-like structure used to secure an airship.

Subcode.Label: Float_Bridge_Site
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Site on a river or canal which has a ramp, piling, and/or pier structures constructed on one or both shores to allow for suitable future crossing operations using float bridge or rafting equipment.

Subcode.Label: Pipeline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A tube for the conveyance of solids, liquids or gases.

Subcode.Label: Storm_Drain
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A collector opening into a pipe or channel to allow the removal of excess runoff water or in some cases sewage.

Subcode.Label: Utility_Cover
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A removable cover or plate which provides access to underground utility tunnels, distribution lines, or drainage systems.

Subcode.Label: Pumping_Station
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A facility to move solids, liquids or gases by means of pressure or suction.

Subcode.Label: Sharp_Curve
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A curve which may cause transportation restrictions.

Subcode.Label: Route_Marker
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An emblem used to designate a road's name or identifying number.

Subcode.Label: Steep_Grade
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Location along any given traveled way where the percent (%) slope (ratio of change in elevation (vertical distance) to horizontal ground distance multiplied by 100) is high enough to slow, hinder, or even stop movement.

Subcode.Label: Station-Misc
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A stopping place for the transfer of passengers and/or freight.

Subcode.Label: Tunnel
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An underground or underwater passage, open at both ends, and usually containing a road or railroad. (See also AQ090)

Subcode.Label: Vehicle_Rest_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A roadside place usually having facilities for people and/or vehicles.

Subcode.Label: Vehicle_Park_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An open land area used for storing or parking vehicles or vessels (including recreational vehicles). (See also AI020 and AK060)

Subcode.Label: Parking_Garage
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A designated, multi-level, structure used for parking and/or storing vehicles.

Subcode.Label: Steps_or_Stair
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A series of steps or stairs reaching from one level to another.

Subcode.Label: Arcade
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A covered passageway composed of arches and pillars usually open at one or both sides.

Subcode.Label: Overhead_Walkway
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An elevated or suspended bridge-like structure providing pedestrian passage.

Subcode.Label: Traffic_Light
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A set of automatic lights (usually red, amber, and green) for controlling road traffic, especially at a road intersection.

Subcode.Label: Street_Lamp
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A lamp intended to illuminate a road.

Subcode.Label: Street_Sign
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A sign placed along a road for the purpose of regulating the flow of traffic (for example: vehicles and/or pedestrians) and/or providing information.

Subcode.Label: Motor_Vehicle_Station
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A building at, or in which, motor vehicles are refuelled, serviced, and sometimes repaired.

Subcode.Label: Weigh_Station
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A building and associated equipment that is used to inspect and weigh motor vehicles.

Subcode.Label: Regulatory_Sign
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A sign placed by an authority charged with the regulation of traffic along a transportation route for the purpose of regulating the flow of traffic (for example: vessels, vehicles and/or pedestrians) and/or providing information pertinent to the control of that traffic.

Subcode.Label: Marshaller
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Aircraft Guidance-Positionning Personnel.

Subcode.Label: Cable
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A single continuous rope-like bundle consisting of multiple strands of fiber, plastic, metal, and/or glass. (See also AT006, AT030 and AT060)

Subcode.Label: Overhead_Cable
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An insulated wire, or group of wires formed into one continuous strand and located above ground or above water surface. (Retired) (See also AT005, AT030 and AT060)

Subcode.Label: Dish_Aerial
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A concave object used for transmitting or receiving electronic signals.

Subcode.Label: Aerial
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A device that is used for emitting and/or sensing electromagnetic energy.

Subcode.Label: Aerial_Farm
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A collection of aerials that are collocated and serve a common purpose.

Subcode.Label: Early_Warning_Radar
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An installation utilizing long range radar to detect approaching aircraft or missiles.

Subcode.Label: Power_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A cable that transmits or distributes electrical power. (See also AT005, AT006 and AT060)

Subcode.Label: Power_Pylon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A pylon or pole used to support a power transmission line.

Subcode.Label: Telepheric
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A transportation system consisting of load cables strung between pylons on which carrier units (for example: cars or buckets intended to transport people, material, and/or equipment) are suspended.

Subcode.Label: Pylon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A pylon or pole used to support one or more cables.

Subcode.Label: Radar
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A device for transmitting and receiving radar emissions.

Subcode.Label: Comm_Building
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A building in which communication signals are processed or controlled.

Subcode.Label: Telephone_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A cable that transmits communication signals. (Rrevised concept but same code). (See also AT005, AT006, and AT030)

Subcode.Label: Telephone_Pylon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A pylon that supports one or more communication lines. (Rrevised concept but same code)

Subcode.Label: Comm_Tower
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A relatively tall structure used for transmitting and/or receiving electronic communication signals. (See also AQ060)

Subcode.Label: High_Water_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The line dividing the backshore and foreshore along a coast or beach as defined by the National Authority.

Subcode.Label: Coastline_or_Shoreline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The line where a land mass is in contact with a body of water.

Subcode.Label: Coastline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line generally following the contact between a land mass and a body of water, based on the low water line, and used as a reference for measuring international boundaries such as Territorial Limits or Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ).

Subcode.Label: Foreshore
Subcode.Concept_Definition: That part of the shore or beach which lies between the low water mark and the coastline/shoreline. The same condition may exist in non-contiguous off-shore areas. (Superseeded by BA023)

Subcode.Label: Nearshore
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Area between the 10 meter depth curve and the low water line defined by either Mean Low Water Springs (MLWS) or Mean Low Low Water (MLLW) as defined by the National Authority. (See also BA020, BA022, and BA023)

Subcode.Label: Backshore
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Area between the normal limit of wave action above either Mean High Water Springs (MHWS) or Mean High High Water (MHHW) as defined by the National Authority and the maximum limit of wave action. (See also BA020, BA021, and BA023)

Subcode.Label: Foreshore
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Area between the low water line defined by Mean Low Water Springs (MLWS) or Mean Low Low Water (MLLW) as appropriate and the normal limit of wave action above Mean High Water Springs (MHWS) or Mean High High Water (MHHW) as appropriate. (See also BA020, BA021, and BA022)

Subcode.Label: Shoreline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line drawn along the normal limit of wave action above either Mean High Water Springs (MHWS) or Mean High High Water (MHHW) as defined by the National Authority.

Subcode.Label: Offshore
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The comparatively flat zone of variable width that extends from the outer margin of the rather steeply sloping shoreface to the edge of the continental shelf.

Subcode.Label: Island
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A land mass smaller than a continent and surrounded by water.

Subcode.Label: Water
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area of water which normally has tidal fluctuations.

Subcode.Label: Beach
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The shore of the sea or lake, sandy or pebbly, brought up by the waves (including the foreshore area). (See also BA020, BA021, BA022 and BA023)

Subcode.Label: Dyke_Crown
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A man-made embankment to contain or hold back water.. (See also DB090)

Subcode.Label: Beach_Exit
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A point from which exit can be made from a beach.

Subcode.Label: Waterbody_Bar
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A shallow ridge or mound of unconsolidated mineral material that is located in a stream channel, at the mouth of a stream, in an estuary, at a lagoon, in the wave-break zone along a coast or at the sea bottom.

Subcode.Label: Harbor
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural or artificial improved body of water providing protection for vessels and anchorage and docking facilities.

Subcode.Label: Harbor_Complex
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Complex feature with possible components: many simple features, and complex features BB011, BC099, BC098. Superseeded by BB005

Subcode.Label: Channel_Edge
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Complex feature with possible components: BC099, BC098. (Retired)

Subcode.Label: Harbour_Waters
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural or artificial improved body of water providing protection for vessels and usually associated with a port.

Subcode.Label: Port
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place provided with terminal and transfer facilities for loading and/or discharging cargo or passengers, usually located in a harbour.

Subcode.Label: Anchorage
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area of water where vessels anchor or may anchor.

Subcode.Label: Anchorage-Complex
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Complex feature with possible components: BB010, BC099, BC098. Superseeded by BB010

Subcode.Label: Anchor_Berth
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A designated area of water where a single vessel, sea plane, oil rig, etc. is anchored or may anchor.

Subcode.Label: Roadstead
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area near the shore where vessels can anchor in safety, usually a shallow indentation in the coast.

Subcode.Label: Anchor
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Device normally placed on the sea bottom and attached to a cable or rope used to position a vessel, boat, or any other floating structure.

Subcode.Label: Berth
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A named or numbered place where a vessel is moored at a wharf..

Subcode.Label: Mooring_Trot
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Complex feature with possible components: BB019, BC098.

Subcode.Label: Basin
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An enclosure containing water for a dock for ships. (Retired; specific basin types are all available as features and this generalized feature is not useful or used.)

Subcode.Label: Bollard
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A post on a wharf used for fastening mooring lines.

Subcode.Label: Groyne
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure which protects a harbor or beach from forces of the sea. (Superseeded by BB041) (See also BB140)

Subcode.Label: Breakwater
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure that protects a waterbody region (for example: a shore, a harbour, and/or an anchorage) from water waves by preventing them from reaching the protected region or reducing their magnitude. (See also BB140 and BB042)

Subcode.Label: Mole
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A loading and discharge place for vessels. It is usually a substantial masonry structure, and often serves as a breakwater on its outer side while offering facilities for ships in its inner side.

Subcode.Label: Groin
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A low artificial wall-like structure of durable material extending from the land to seaward for a particular purpose, such as to prevent coast erosion.. (See also BB140 and BB041)

Subcode.Label: Calling-In_Point
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A specified point some distance from the harbor at which a vessel's navigator notifies the harbor authority of his ship's position. (Note that this is not the same as GA055 which is for aircraft only).

Subcode.Label: Mooring_Facility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure used for mooring/warping a ship or as protection for harbor constructions.

Subcode.Label: Dolphin
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A post or group of posts used for mooring, warping a ship or as an aid to navigation.

Subcode.Label: Shoreline_Constr
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A fixed (not afloat) artificial structure attached to the land. Shoreline constructions are normally used for berthing and protection.

Subcode.Label: Shoreline_Ramp
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A ramp-like structure on a shoreline that is intended to facilitate the movement of vessels and/or materials (for example: logs) into or out of the water.

Subcode.Label: Drydock
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure, providing support for a vessel, which has a means of removing water so that the bottom of the vessel can be exposed.

Subcode.Label: Dry_Dock_Basin
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The reservoir in a dry dock bounded by the dry dock wall and dry dock gate.

Subcode.Label: Dry_Dock_Wall
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The wall of a dry dock.

Subcode.Label: Dock
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An artificially enclosed body of water within which vessels may moor and which may have gates used to regulate the interior water level.

Subcode.Label: Fish_Stakes
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Poles or stakes placed in shallow water to catch fish.

Subcode.Label: Fishing_Harbor
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A harbor which is primarily used by fishing vessels.

Subcode.Label: Fish_Trap
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A fence or enclosure set in water to catch fish.

Subcode.Label: Tunny
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area where nets used for catching tunny (tuna) may be found.

Subcode.Label: Fish_Trap_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area containing structures (usually portable) for catching fish.

Subcode.Label: Gridiron
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A flat frame, usually of parallel timber baulks, erected on the foreshore so that a vessel may dry out on it for painting or repair at low water.

Subcode.Label: Jetty
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A man-made barrier built out into, or in the water, primarily to restrain or direct currents and waves. (See also AQ030 and BB040)

Subcode.Label: Boat_Landing
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place where boats receive or discharge passengers and freight, but lacking most port facilities.

Subcode.Label: Landing_Place
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place on shore where landing from the sea is possible.

Subcode.Label: Landing_Stair
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Steps at the shoreline as the connection between land and water on different levels.

Subcode.Label: Maritime_Station
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A facility occupied by a governmental (maritime related) or harbor authority, providing specific services to vessels. A signal station is a structure (building, tower, mast, etc.), which conveys information visually from station to ship.

Subcode.Label: Mooring_Ring
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A metal ring attached to a structure and used to secure a vessel.

Subcode.Label: Loading_Facility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A facility located offshore for loading and unloading cargo.

Subcode.Label: Mobile_Offshore_Drill_Unit
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A self-contained floatable or floating drilling machine that appears as an offshore working platform when in position for operations.

Subcode.Label: Oyster_Bed
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place in shallow water where oysters and mussels breed and may be cultivated. (Retire; if cultivated then this is a Marine Farm, if not it is normally treated as a bottom characteristic.)

Subcode.Label: Pier_Generic
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure primarily used as berthing places for vessels.

Subcode.Label: Pier
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A long, narrow STRUCTURE extending into a WATERBODY to afford a berthing place for VESSELs or to serve as a promenade; a pier.

Subcode.Label: Wharf
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A STRUCTURE serving as a berthing place for VESSELs; a wharf.

Subcode.Label: Quay
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A platform STRUCTURE lying alongside or projecting into water for loading and unloading ships.

Subcode.Label: Other
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A pier-type other than those listed above.

Subcode.Label: Fender
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A protective structure designed to cushion the impact of a vessel and prevent damage. (Retired; concept is at best semi-permanent and generally small. Possibly shoud be considered as a type of shoreline construction.)

Subcode.Label: Floating_Dock
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A dock which normally consists of a bottom pontoon, on which a ship can be lifted out of the water, and two side walls to give stability to the bottom pontoon.

Subcode.Label: Pump_Out_Facility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place on land to where ships can pump waste liquids.

Subcode.Label: Small_Craft_Facility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An installation with a certain function or service generally of interest for small craft or pleasure boats.

Subcode.Label: Ice_Boom
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Floating barriers, anchored to the bottom, used to deflect the path of floating ice in order to prevent the obstruction of locks, intakes, etc., and to prevent damage to bridge piers and other structures.

Subcode.Label: Ramp
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A partially submerged hard surfaced area on a shoreline for launching and retrieving vessels or vehicles.

Subcode.Label: Log_Ramp
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An inclined plane used to dump logs into the water for transport, or to haul logs out of the water for processing.

Subcode.Label: Rip_Rap
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A loose assemblage of broken stones or similar material erected in water or on soft ground as a foundation or to protect the underlying surface from erosion.

Subcode.Label: Shore_Revetment
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Facing of stone or other material placed along the edge of a stream, river or canal to stabilize the bank and to protect it from the erosive action of the stream.

Subcode.Label: Seawall
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure built to protect the shore from erosion.

Subcode.Label: Slipway
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A prepared slope for launching and recovering vessels.

Subcode.Label: Shipyard
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A large enclosed area adjoining the sea or a major river, including facilities in which ships are built or repaired.

Subcode.Label: Watering_Place
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place where vessels can replenish their water supply. (Retired; this is coded as a hydrographic feature, it is better expressed as a type of facility, and is not known to be in current use.)

Subcode.Label: Pilot_Boarding_Place
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A location offshore where a pilot may board a vessel in preparation to piloting it through local waters.

Subcode.Label: Beacon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A fixed visual or electronic aid to navigation.

Subcode.Label: Buoy
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A floating object, other than a lightship, moored or anchored to the bottom and serving as an aid to navigation.

Subcode.Label: Lateral_Buoy
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A buoy used to indicate a lateral limit of navigable water.

Subcode.Label: Leading_Light
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Two or more lights forming a leading line of a course to be followed.

Subcode.Label: Navigation_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line generated by the straight line connection between two navigational aids, and which extends towards the area of navigational interest.

Subcode.Label: Radar_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Mid-channel lines corresponding to the lines in harbor radar displays.

Subcode.Label: Radar_Range
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Indicates the coverage of a sea area by a radar surveillance station. Inside this area a vessel may request shore based radar assistance, particularly in poor visibility.

Subcode.Label: Maritime_Radiobeacon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An electronic aid to maritime navigation consisting of a radio transmitter that broadcasts distinctive signals.

Subcode.Label: Lights_in_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Lights marking area limits, cable alignment, alignments for anchoring, etc., not marking direction or course.

Subcode.Label: Light
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A specially constructed device which displays a luminous or lighted aid to navigation. (See also BC050)

Subcode.Label: Lighthouse
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A distinctive structure exhibiting light(s) designed to serve as an aid to navigation. (See also BC040)

Subcode.Label: Marker
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A colored (usually white) mark on a cliff, rock, wall, etc. which is a conspicuous landmark for marine navigation.

Subcode.Label: Light_Sector
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A sector defined by bearings from seaward within which a light shows a specified character or color, or is obscured.

Subcode.Label: Light_Vessel
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A distinctively marked manned vessel anchored or moored at a defined point to serve as an aid to navigation.

Subcode.Label: Perches
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A small marker used to identify channels or to mark dangers such as rocks, shoals, etc. (See also BD100 and BD140)

Subcode.Label: Nav_Mark-Afloat
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Complex feature with possible components made of many simple features only. (Retired; complex features no longer needed.)

Subcode.Label: Nav_Mark-Fixed
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Complex feature with possible components made of many simple features only. (Retired; complex features no longer needed.)

Subcode.Label: Leading_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A track which passes through one or more (usually two) clearly defined objects, along which a vessel can safely travel.

Subcode.Label: Fog_Signal
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A warning signal transmitted by a vessel, or aid to navigation, during periods of low visibility. Also, the device producing such a signal.

Subcode.Label: Direction-Buoyage
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A point (symbol) placed in a dataset to indicate the direction defining a lateral buoyage system, such as the International Association of Lighthouse Authorities (IALA) Lateral System where the orientation is not otherwise discernable from the configuration of shoreline and waterways due to limited geographic extent or other constraints. (Retired; this cartographic object was intended to support portrayal but appears to have never been used.)

Subcode.Label: Sound_Signal_Device
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An acoustic aid to navigation consisting of a device that generates distinctive audible sounds.

Subcode.Label: Topmark
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A characteristic shape secured at the top of a buoy or beacon to aid in its identification. (IHO S-32)

Subcode.Label: Underwater
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A known underwater object or area, known to be dangerous to surface navigation. (Retired; this feature is inappropriately generic - if the danger is known then the type of danger will also be known and a more suitable feature type used.)
Subcode.Recommended_Dataset_Component: Hydrography Network Lineal Figure Pt, Hydrography Network Areal Figure Pt

Subcode.Label: Mine-Naval
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An explosive device used in naval warfare located on or below the sea.

Subcode.Label: Small_Bottom_Object
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An object protruding above the water body bottom whose greatest dimension is less than five metres.

Subcode.Label: Large_Bottom_Object
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An object protruding above the water body bottom of which at least one component of height, width or length is a minimum of 5 metres.

Subcode.Label: Misc_Underwater
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An object or area on the sea floor or underwater that is not identified by any other code in this specification. (Retired; Miscellaneous Feature Type (ZD019) may be used as appropriate). (Also see BD000)

Subcode.Label: Breakers
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Waves which break over off-lying shoals or near the shore. (See also BD080)

Subcode.Label: Crib
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A framework structure submerged or above water used to support pipelines, sewer lines, or outfalls.

Subcode.Label: Discolored_Water
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area of sea water having a color distinctly different from the surrounding water.

Subcode.Label: Eddy
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Circular movements of water running contrary to the main current.

Subcode.Label: Foul_Ground
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A region of comparatively shallow water strewn with rocks, boulders, coral, wreckage, or other obstructions, making it unsuitable for anchoring, grounding, or ground fishing.

Subcode.Label: Seaweed
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A region of marine plants that grow in long narrow ribbons.

Subcode.Label: Aquatic_Vegetation
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A region of waterborne cellular or vascular plants (for example: algae, grasses, reeds, and water hyacinths).

Subcode.Label: Obstruction
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A danger to navigation, the exact nature of which is not specified, or has not been determined.
Subcode.Recommended_Dataset_Component: Hydrography Network Lineal Figure Pt, Hydrography Network Areal Figure Pt

Subcode.Label: Log_Boom
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line of connected, floating timbers as across a river or enclosing a water area to keep logs ready for the sawmill from floating away; also, the enclosed area. (Supersede by (new) Log Boom (BD075) and (new) Booming Ground (BD076); these are different concepts and can't be represented by a single feature type.)

Subcode.Label: Pontoon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A broad, flat-bottomed floating structure without sheer, rectangular in shape, resembling a barge.

Subcode.Label: Oil_Barrier
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A construction to dam oil flow on water.

Subcode.Label: Chain_or_Wire
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A physical connection between two independent objects, e.g., between: anchor and mooring buoy; anchor and offshore platform; hulk and bollard on land.

Subcode.Label: Log_Boom
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A floating barrier used to enclose and contain rafted logs.

Subcode.Label: Booming_Ground
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A marine region used as a staging area for logs.

Subcode.Label: Fishing_Facility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A tool or structure in shallow water for fishing purposes which can be an obstruction to ships in general.

Subcode.Label: Tide_Rip
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Short, breaking waves occurring when a current passes over a shoal or other submarine obstruction or meets a contrary current or wind. Tide rips occur when one or more of the currents are tidal. (Retired; these are different types of water turbulence concepts and should not be combined as a single feature) .(See also BD010)

Subcode.Label: Pile
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A long, heavy timber or section of steel, concrete, etc., forced into the earth to serve as a support, as for a pier. (See also BC080 and BD140)

Subcode.Label: Platform_Generic
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure placed in the sea and used for production loading and discharge or observation/research facilities.

Subcode.Label: Oil_Rig
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A RIG assembled primarily for the purpose of drilling an oil WELL; an oil drilling rig.

Subcode.Label: Production_Platform
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A Production_Platform-type STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: Research_Platform
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A Research_Platform-type STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: Platform_ALP
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A Platform_ALP-type (Articulated Loading Platform) STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: SALM
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A SALM-type (Single anchor leg mooring) STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: Mooring_Tower
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A Mooring_Tower-type STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: Artificial_Island
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An Artificial_Island-type STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: FPSO_Vessel
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A FPSO_Vessel-type (Floating production, storage and off-loading vessel) STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: Accom_Platform
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An Accommodation Platform-type STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: Other
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An Other-type STRUCTURE placed in a WATERBODY and used: for production, loading, and discharge; as an OBSERVATION_STATION; or as a SCIENCE_FACILITY; an offshore platform.

Subcode.Label: Offshore_Platform
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An offshore structure with a flat surface raised above the sea, used as a working stage for conducting offshore operations. (Superseded by Platform (BD110) as the current concept is unnecessarily specialized and effectively redundant).

Subcode.Label: Prod_Installation
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An installation for the exploitation of natural resources. (Retired; definition is unclear and it appears to be unused).

Subcode.Label: Offshore_Construction
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An artificial structure that is located offshore.

Subcode.Label: Ledge
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A narrow, flat surface or shelf, especially one that projects, as from a wall of rock. (Retired; unnecessarily specialized and not in current use)

Subcode.Label: Reef
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A rocky or coral elevation at or near enough to the surface of the sea to be a danger to surface navigation.

Subcode.Label: Pingo
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A cone or dome shaped mound or hill of peat or soil, usually with a core of ice. It is found in tundra regions and is produced by the pressure of water or ice accumulating underground and pushing upward.

Subcode.Label: Cay
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A small insular feature, which may contain scant vegetation; usually composed of sand or coral. Often applied to smaller coral shoals.

Subcode.Label: Boom
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A floating barrier used to protect a river or harbor mouth or to create a sheltered area for storage purposes.

Subcode.Label: Fish_Haven
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area on a water body bottom established to simulate a natural reef and intended to enhance fishery resources and commercial and/or recreational fishing opportunities.

Subcode.Label: Rock
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An isolated rocky formation or a single large stone above or below the water surface.

Subcode.Label: Snag_or_Stump
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A stem or a trunk of a tree below the surface of water. (See also BC080 and BD100)

Subcode.Label: Wreck
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The ruined remains of a vessel.

Subcode.Label: Hulk
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A permanently moored ship.

Subcode.Label: Non_Submarine_Contact
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An object on the sea floor (for example: a wreck) that, when detected (for example: using acoustic or magnetic sensors), appears similar to and could be confused with a operating submarine.

Subcode.Label: Depth_Curve
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A navigational safety line indicating that no sounding of a lesser depth exists seaward of the line, but greater depths may occur on the shallow side of the line.

Subcode.Label: Depth_Contour
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line connecting points of equal depth at and below the hydrographic datum.

Subcode.Label: Depth_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Water area containing soundings within a defined range of values permanently at or below sounding datum.

Subcode.Label: Sounding
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A measured water depth or spot depth which has been reduced to chart datum.

Subcode.Label: Low_Water_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Delineates an area that covers and uncovers depending on the elevation of the surface above chart datum.

Subcode.Label: Sand_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Delineates an area of sand that covers and uncovers depending on the elevation of the surface above chart datum. (Retired: Consider alternatively using Feature: Foreshore (BA023); note that as a line (not an area) this is a type of Low Water Line).

Subcode.Label: Mud_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Delineates an area of mud that covers and uncovers depending on the elevation of the surface above chart datum. (Retired; Consider alternatively using Feature: Foreshore (BA023); note that as a line (not an area) this is a type of Low Water Line).

Subcode.Label: Bottom_Return
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An object identified from the bottom background by side-scan sonar. (Retired; a "return" is not an object; AML will address this with a more appropriate set of features).

Subcode.Label: Track_Swath
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Area of horizontal depth coverage recorded by SONAR array systems.

Subcode.Label: Track_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The actual path or route of a craft over the ground or sea bottom. (Revised)

Subcode.Label: Beach_Profile
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A representation of the three dimensional relief of the bottom along a line or series of connected lines and based on depth contours, soundings, and other measurements of the depth at or below the hydrographic datum.

Subcode.Label: Bottom_Char
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Designations used on surveys and charts to indicate the consistency, color, and classification of the sea floor, as determined by sampling methods.

Subcode.Label: Bottom_Feature
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A significant configuration of underwater bottom topography.

Subcode.Label: Seabed_Impact_Scour
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A clearing away of mud or other seabed deposits by the action of an object impacting and/or traversing along the seabed before settling.

Subcode.Label: Current_Flow
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A location at which currents, tides, and/or other types of water movement are specified.`(Revised)

Subcode.Label: Tideway
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural watercourse in intertidal areas where water flows during the ebb and flow.

Subcode.Label: Water_Turbulence
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The disturbance of water caused by the interaction of any combination of waves, currents, eddies, tidal streams, wind, shoal patches and obstructions.

Subcode.Label: Water_Current_Region
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A waterbody region in which a water current persists.

Subcode.Label: Tide_Gauge
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An instrument for measuring the height of the tide.

Subcode.Label: Tidal_Obs_Station
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Place for which tabulated tidal stream data are given.

Subcode.Label: Tidal_Diagram
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A graph or chartlet showing the average speed of the flood and ebb currents at different periods of the current cycle. (Supersede by (renamed) Water Movement Data Location (BG010) to emphasize the data-capture location, rather than its presentation).

Subcode.Label: Water
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Any known inland waterway body, such as: lake/pond, reservoir, river/stream, etc. requiring separation into individual features due to status/type grouping that is currently indeterminable.

Subcode.Label: Aqueduct
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A pipe or artificial channel designed to transport water from a remote source, usually by gravity. (See also BH110)

Subcode.Label: Intake
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place where water is taken into a channel or pipe from a river, or other body of water e.g. to supply an aqueduct or water works.

Subcode.Label: Qanat_Shaft
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A vertical shaft that provides access to an underground aqueduct and which is part of a qanat system.

Subcode.Label: Bog
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A poorly drained or periodically flooded area, excluding tidal waters, with soil rich in plant residue.

Subcode.Label: Canal
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A man-made or improved natural waterway used for transportation.

Subcode.Label: Ditch
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A channel constructed for the purpose of irrigation or drainage.

Subcode.Label: Filtration_Bed
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area containing layers of material used to filter or aerate water.

Subcode.Label: Aquaculture_Facility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A facility involved in the culturing or farming (including harvesting) of aquatic organisms (for example: fish, mollusks, crustaceans, plants, crocodiles, alligators or amphibians) using techniques designed to increase the production of the organisms in question beyond the natural capacity of the environment (for example: regular stocking, feeding and protection from predators).

Subcode.Label: Fish_Farm
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An enclosure of water used for the breeding and/or rearing of fish.

Subcode.Label: Fish_Farm_Facility
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A facility involved in the raising of fish commercially in tanks or landlocked enclosures, usually for food.

Subcode.Label: Flume
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An open, inclined channel which carries water for use in such operations as mining or logging.

Subcode.Label: Water_Race
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An artificial channel for a current of water, especially one built to provide water for industrial or agricultural purposes or for transporting water-borne materials.

Subcode.Label: Ford
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A shallow place in a body of water used as a crossing. (See also AQ062)

Subcode.Label: Fountain
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An artificial spring with water.

Subcode.Label: Hummock
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area of higher elevation within a swamp, bog, or marsh.

Subcode.Label: Lake_or_Pond
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A large body of water entirely surrounded by land. (Revised) (See also BH130)

Subcode.Label: Pond
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A small reservoir-like body of generally still water.

Subcode.Label: Inland_Waterbody
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A body of water that is entirely surrounded by land.

Subcode.Label: Low_Land
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area periodically covered by flood water, excluding tidal waters. (See also BH095, ED010, and ED020)

Subcode.Label: Flooded_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Land subject to controlled inundation (i.e. flooded by the regulation of the level of water impounded by a dam or beaver dam), and is normally associated with permanently flooded areas in which trees are still standing. Also known as inundated land.

Subcode.Label: Marsh_or_Swamp
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A saturated area, at times covered with water, supporting vegetation which may include trees. (See also BH090, ED010, and ED020)

Subcode.Label: Moat
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A trench usually filled with water, that surrounds a body of land.

Subcode.Label: Penstock
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A pipeline or channel generally used by hydroelectric plants or water mills to transport water by gravity and under pressure. (See also BH010)

Subcode.Label: Phreatic_Water
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Water situated underground but reachable by wells.

Subcode.Label: Rapids
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place in a stream or river where the current is swift and the surface is usually broken by boulders and rocks.

Subcode.Label: Reservoir
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A man-made enclosure or area formed for the storage of water. (See also BH080)

Subcode.Label: Rice_Field
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area periodically covered with water used for growing rice.

Subcode.Label: River_or_Stream
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural flowing watercourse.

Subcode.Label: River_Bank
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The limit line between the water area of a river and the area of land.

Subcode.Label: River_Vanishing_Pt
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Point at which a river or stream passes into the ground.

Subcode.Label: Salt_Pan
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A flat area of natural surface salt deposits.

Subcode.Label: Salt_Evaporator
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Shallow pools, normally man-made, used for the natural evaporation of water for the collection of salt.

Subcode.Label: Sebkha
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural depression in arid or semi-arid regions whose bed is covered with salt encrusted clayey soil.

Subcode.Label: Spillway
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A passage for surplus water to run over or around a dam.

Subcode.Label: Water_Hole
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural outflow of water from below the ground surface. (See also AA050 and BH075)

Subcode.Label: Water_Hole
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A small natural terrain depression in which water collects, especially a pool where animals come to drink.

Subcode.Label: Spring
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A flow of water rising or welling naturally from the earth.

Subcode.Label: Resurgence
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The location at which a watercourse re-emerges from the terrain at the end of an underground part of its course.

Subcode.Label: Trough
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A man-made open water container for animal drinking.

Subcode.Label: Waterfall
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A vertical or nearly vertical descent of water.

Subcode.Label: Lagoon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Open body of water separated from the sea by a sand bank or coral reef.

Subcode.Label: Channel
Subcode.Concept_Definition: That part of a body of water, sometimes dredged, deep enough for navigation through an area otherwise not navigable. It is usually marked by a single or double line of navigational aids.

Subcode.Label: Thalweg
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An imaginary line connecting the points of lowest bed elevation in a river channel.

Subcode.Label: Surf_Drainage
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Surface drainage feature which is of a minor nature and which is not included in other feature codings in this specification. (Retired; Miscellaneous Feature Type (ZD019) may be used as appropriate).

Subcode.Label: Inland_Shoreline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The land-water boundary for all inland hydrographic features having shorelines, Lake /Pond (BH080), or Island (BA030).

Subcode.Label: Waterwork
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An establishment for storing, purifying, and supplying an area or town with water.

Subcode.Label: Water_Well
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A shaft sunk into the ground to reach and tap a supply of water.

Subcode.Label: Irrigation_System
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A system for supplying land with water, usually by a network of channels or pipes.

Subcode.Label: Shallow_Water_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: That part of an inland body of water where the depth is relatively slight (less than 1 metre) and thus likely to limit the passage of watercraft.

Subcode.Label: River_Nav_Route
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The route in a river suitable for the largest allowed vessels. (Superseded by more general Maritime Route (FC165); use attribution to distinguish the type of waterbody/route) .(See also FC168)

Subcode.Label: Boat_Lift
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A mechanical device for lifting vessels between two levels other than a lock. (See also BI030)

Subcode.Label: Ship_Elevator
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A device used to raise ships vertically between water bodies with different elevations.

Subcode.Label: Cistern
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A man-made container used for collection or storage of rain water.

Subcode.Label: Dam_or_Weir
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A permanent barrier across a watercourse used to impound water or to control its flow. (See also BI040)

Subcode.Label: Lock
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An enclosure with a pair or series of gates used for raising or lowering vessels as they pass from one water level to another. (See also BI005)

Subcode.Label: Lock_Basin
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A wet dock in a waterway permitting a ship to pass from one level to another (IHO S-32) (See also BI030)

Subcode.Label: Lock_Gate
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The pair of massive hinged doors at each end of a lock.

Subcode.Label: Lock_Wall
Subcode.Concept_Definition: One of the pair of walls, usually masonary, that contain a lock basin and support the lock gates.

Subcode.Label: Sluice
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An open, inclined conduit fitted with a gate for regulating water flow and may be employed in mine ore washing operations. (See also BI020 and BI040)

Subcode.Label: Sluice_Gate
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A gate used to regulate the flow of water. (See also BI020 and BI039)

Subcode.Label: Gate
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A structure that may be swung, drawn, or lowered to block an entrance or passageway.

Subcode.Label: Caisson
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The gate at the end of a drydock which excludes the water after pumping out the dock. The pumping engines are often located in the caisson.

Subcode.Label: Flood_Barrage
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An artificial obstruction placed in a water course to increase the depth or to divert it.

Subcode.Label: Flood_Control_Structure
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An artificial structure or gate that is utilized as a defense against flooding or storm surges.

Subcode.Label: Basin_Gate
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A gate that impounds water within a basin or chamber that is used by watercraft.

Subcode.Label: Intake_Tower
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A tower-like structure associated with a dam or water source and used for the intake of water.

Subcode.Label: Fish_Ladder
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A series of ascending pools constructed to enable fish to swim upstream around or over a dam.

Subcode.Label: Gauging
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A device which monitors stream flow.

Subcode.Label: Boat_Basin
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A section of canal or navigable waterway in which a barge or other vessel can be turned.

Subcode.Label: Moraine
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An accumulation of soil and stone debris deposited by a glacier.

Subcode.Label: Glacier
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A large mass of snow and ice moving slowly down a slope or valley from above the snowline.

Subcode.Label: Crevasse
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A deep crack or fissure in a glacier that results from differential movement of ice.

Subcode.Label: Ice_Cliff
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The vertical face of a glacier or ice shelf.

Subcode.Label: Ice_Peak
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A rocky peak projecting above a surrounding ice field that may be perpetually covered with ice.

Subcode.Label: Ice_Shelf
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A sheet of thick ice, with level or undulating surface, attached to the land but mostly afloat which is bounded on the seaward side by an Ice Cliff (BJ040).

Subcode.Label: Pack_Ice
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area of ice formed by the drifting and crushing together of floating pieces of ice.

Subcode.Label: Polar_Ice
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The heaviest, thickest form of ice over land or water. (See also BJ100)

Subcode.Label: Ice_Cap
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A permanent layer of ice covering a tract of land (especially a polar region) or the top of a mountain.

Subcode.Label: Snow_or_Ice_Field
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A large area permanently covered by snow or ice over land or water. (See also BJ080)

Subcode.Label: Land_Snow_Ice_Field
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A large land area permanently covered by snow and/or ice.

Subcode.Label: Tundra
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A prairie-like region in the Arctic and Subarctic zones which sustains a growth of low vegetation.

Subcode.Label: Acoustic_Station
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A device equipped for the collection of acoustic data.

Subcode.Label: Magnetic_Station
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A device equipped for the collection of magnetic data.

Subcode.Label: Collection_Device
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A device used for the collection of unspecified hydrographic and oceanographic data.

Subcode.Label: Contour_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line connecting points having the same vertical datum value.

Subcode.Label: Ridge_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line representation of a ridge top.

Subcode.Label: Valley_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line representation of the lowest part of a valley.

Subcode.Label: Breakline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Line representing the demarcation of a sudden and significant change in the gradient of the terrain relief.

Subcode.Label: Spot_Elevation
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A designated location with an elevation value relative to a vertical datum.

Subcode.Label: Water_Elevation
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A location with a generalized elevation value relative to a vertical datum associated with an inland, usually confined, water body.

Subcode.Label: Contour_Polygon
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An arbitrary area outline created to establish elevation as polygons.

Subcode.Label: Surface_Triangle
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A set of three spot elevations defining a terrain region of constant slope and aspect.

Subcode.Label: Terrain_Constraint_Point
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A point used to constrain the terrain elevation

Subcode.Label: Terrain_Constraint_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A line consisting of multiple segments whose vertices and edges are used to constrain the terrain elevation

Subcode.Label: Terrain_Constraint_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A multi-triangle convex or concave area whose vertices and edges are used to constrain the terrain elevation

Subcode.Label: Asphalt_Lake
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural pool of liquid asphalt.

Subcode.Label: Alkali_Flat
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A sterile plain containing an excess of alkali usually occurring in the bottom of an under drained basin in an arid or semi-arid region. The ground may be soft and have low shearing and bearing strength, and a high organic content.

Subcode.Label: Ground
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The surface soil characteristics of the earth.

Subcode.Label: Barren
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Ground so disturbed as to have no identifiable coverage.

Subcode.Label: Land_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area not permanently or temporarily covered by water.

Subcode.Label: Land_Region
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area of natural scenery on land. It is defined by its geographical characteristics and known by its proper name.

Subcode.Label: Land_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A geographically defined part of the land.

Subcode.Label: Land_Morphology_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A region of the land surface that is homogeneous with respect to form.

Subcode.Label: Cliff
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A steep, vertical, or overhanging face of rock or earth. (See also DB110)

Subcode.Label: Cave
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural subterranean chamber or series of chambers open to the Earth's surface.

Subcode.Label: Hill
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A small, isolated elevation, smaller than a mountain.

Subcode.Label: Crevice
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A narrow fissure, crack, or rift in the Earth's surface, snow or ice. (Supersede by (new) Crevice (DB061) and Crevasse (BJ031); these are different concepts and should not be combined).

Subcode.Label: Crevice
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A narrow opening or fissure produced by a crack in the land, especially in rock.

Subcode.Label: Cut
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An excavation of the Earth's surface to provide passage for a road, railroad, canal, etc.

Subcode.Label: Cut_Line
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The demarcation line between a cut and the surrounding land surface.

Subcode.Label: Cut_Face
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The face of an excavation within a cut.

Subcode.Label: Depression
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A low area surrounded by higher ground.

Subcode.Label: Embankment
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A raised long mound of earth or other material. (See also BA051)

Subcode.Label: Esker
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A long, narrow ridge of sand and gravel deposited by a glacial stream.

Subcode.Label: Fault
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A fracture in the Earth's crust with displacement on one side of the fracture relative to the other. (See also DB010)

Subcode.Label: Geothermal_Feature
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A terrain surface feature controlled by or derived from the heat of the Earth's interior.

Subcode.Label: Misc_Obstacle
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Obstacle feature which is of a minor nature and which is not covered by another feature coding in this specification. (Retired; Miscellaneous Feature Type (ZD019) may be used as appropriate).

Subcode.Label: Mountain_Pass
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A natural route through a low place in a mountain range.
Subcode.Recommended_Dataset_Component: Road Network Lineal, Railroad Network Lineal

Subcode.Label: Rock_Formation
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A visual topographic outcrop, layers or beds of rock.

Subcode.Label: Boulder
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A conspicuous isolated rocky formation or single large stone existing in its entirety above the high water mark. From offshore it would appear to a mariner as a single point on land and would be appropriate for use in navigation.

Subcode.Label: Sand_Dune
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Ridges or hills of sand.

Subcode.Label: Slope_Category
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area enclosing a group of slope values falling within a set range. (Superseded by Slope Polygon (SA050); identical concepts and this one does not appear to be in current use).

Subcode.Label: Volcano
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A mountain or hill, often conical, formed around a vent in the earth's crust through which molten rock, ash, or gases are or have been expelled.

Subcode.Label: Submerged_Volcano
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An underwater hill or mountain situated over an opening or openings in the Earth's crust through which lava, steam, and/or gases, are or have been expelled.

Subcode.Label: Crater
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A bowl-shaped depression in the terrain, usually round and with steep sides.

Subcode.Label: Volcanic_Dike
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A steep ridge of igneous rock.

Subcode.Label: Gully_or_Gorge
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A long, narrow, deep erosion with steep banks.

Subcode.Label: Landslide_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A mass of land, with a high potential of slipping down from a mountain, hill, etc.

Subcode.Label: Landslide
Subcode.Concept_Definition: The mass of earth or rock which has slipped down from a mountain or cliff.

Subcode.Label: Undermined_Land
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Area undermined through mining activities that has already partly subsided or that is in the process of subsiding.

Subcode.Label: Fan
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A gently sloping fan shaped feature usually found near the lower termination of a canyon.

Subcode.Label: Cliff-Bottomline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Bottomline of a steep slope.

Subcode.Label: Cliff-Topline
Subcode.Concept_Definition: Topline of a steep slope.

Subcode.Label: Ground_Movement_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area affected by vertical and/or horizontal movements of the Earth surface due to geological forces, ground instability and/or a changing stress-state, leading to volume changes within the soil.

Subcode.Label: Volcanic_Appearance
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area of the Earth's surface that is affected by volcanic structures and/or activity.

Subcode.Label: Cropland
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area that has been tilled for the planting of crops. (See also EA040, EA050, and EA055)

Subcode.Label: Hedgerow
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A continuous growth of shrubbery planted as a fence, a boundary, or a wind break.

Subcode.Label: Nursery
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A place where shrubs, flowers, plants and trees are grown for transplanting, seed or grafting.

Subcode.Label: Botanical_Garden
Subcode.Concept_Definition: A cultural area where plants and/or trees are displayed.

Subcode.Label: Plantation
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area covered by systematic plantings of trees which yield fruits, nuts or other products. (See also EA010, EA050 and EA055)

Subcode.Label: Vineyard
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area covered by the systematic planting of grape vines. (See also EA010, EA040 and EA055)

Subcode.Label: Hops
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area covered by the systematic planting of hop vines. (See also EA010, EA040 and EA050)

Subcode.Label: Horticultural_Area
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area used for the cultivation of vegetables, fruits and/or flowers as well as for the raising of cultivated plants.

Subcode.Label: Grassland
Subcode.Concept_Definition: An area composed of uncultured plants which have little or no woody tissue.

Subcode.Label: Grass_or_Scrub_or_Brush

Subcode.Label: Savanna

Subcode.Label: Brush

Subcode.Label: Scrubland
